WEBVTT

00:01.364 --> 00:02.866
title, leaving the legislature. 1983

00:02.886 --> 00:09.154
was a turnaround year in many ways. The family had 
been instrumental in starting a bank in College

00:10.435 --> 00:16.783
Station. We had oil and gas revenue on our land out 
in the country. and I was still chairman of the

00:25.799 --> 00:31.984
House Appropriations Committee under a new 
speaker.

00:35.127 --> 00:55.705
I had not given serious consideration to leaving 
the legislature until I was approached by the A&M

00:35.127 --> 00:55.705
System Board of Regents about becoming their 
executive secretary and would be the legislative

00:35.127 --> 00:55.705
liaison to the legislature. The more I thought 
about it, the more sense that it made. I had always

01:01.386 --> 01:13.225
worked in the best interest of the system and 
enjoyed my relationship with the legislature.

01:14.747 --> 01:21.237
There was also the possibility that the oil and gas 
revenue would suddenly dry up. and would again put

01:22.600 --> 01:28.648
finances in a pretty tight situation. In 
addition, I had served five terms as chairman of

01:30.370 --> 01:43.427
the House Appropriations Committee and began to 
grow somewhat weary of the

01:44.892 --> 01:57.228
position as it required a new training program 
each time because there was about a 50% turnover in

01:44.892 --> 01:57.228
membership in the committee each session. 
Committee members that were served on the

01:58.149 --> 02:14.190
Appropriations Committee were often tapped in 
the next session to serve as committee chairman

01:58.149 --> 02:14.190
and were then therefore removed from their 
position as a member of the Appropriations

01:58.149 --> 02:14.190
Committee. Discussions with the Board of Regents 
began in earnest following the regular session of

02:15.014 --> 02:26.353
the legislature in 1983. By late 1983, I had made

02:26.573 --> 02:38.052
a decision to leave the legislature and

02:40.158 --> 02:48.590
accept a position with the Secretary of the Board 
should the Board of Regents choose to elect me. On

02:51.273 --> 02:56.681
or about the first of November, I announced that I 
would not be a candidate for re-election. Later

02:57.783 --> 03:08.157
that month, when the Board of Regents met, they 
tentatively approved my appointment as

02:57.783 --> 03:08.157
Executive Secretary of the Board. It was not 
finally approved until the meeting in January

03:08.491 --> 03:23.935
about

03:08.491 --> 03:23.935
the same date that I assumed the position upon 
resigning from the legislature. It is my

03:25.697 --> 03:36.574
understanding that at the very last minute before 
the board acted upon the minute order in November

03:25.697 --> 03:36.574
that a concession was made to the Chancellor to 
make it a dual position, that is, Executive

03:36.740 --> 03:49.219
Secretary of the Board of Regents and Vice 
Chancellor for State Affairs. By doing it this

03:50.420 --> 04:05.042
way, the Chancellor felt like that I would become a 
part of his staff and he would have more of a role in

03:50.420 --> 04:05.042
legislative affairs. I never viewed it as any 
other way except that the Chancellor would play a

04:05.680 --> 04:25.691
very significant role in legislative affairs and 
could see no reason why the dual role would not work

04:05.680 --> 04:25.691
very well since it would really not change 
anything as far as I was concerned.

04:28.936 --> 04:32.481
Shortly after my appointment it was suggested 
that I have an office in the chancellor's suite,

04:33.237 --> 04:43.671
but I declined and suggested I would prefer not to 
do that. I felt like I could operate more

04:44.492 --> 04:52.022
efficiently out of one office as opposed to two 
offices. During the time I was in the legislature,

04:52.222 --> 05:05.763
I operated out of about three or four offices and 
found it rather inefficient to do so, although

04:52.222 --> 05:05.763
there was nothing that I could be done about that 
arrangement while I was in the legislature. Other

05:07.145 --> 05:20.406
than the one conversation regarding the 
suggestion that I have an office in the

05:07.145 --> 05:20.406
chancellor's suite, the issue never came up again 
until many years later. A resignation effective

05:21.263 --> 05:36.948
on January the 15th, 1984, forced the then 
Governor White to call a special election for my

05:21.263 --> 05:36.948
replacement. At that time, there was a need for a 
special session dealing with public school

05:38.250 --> 05:48.486
finance, sometime during 1984. The election was 
called for during

05:51.568 --> 06:11.813
the spring break of March of 1984 and the fact that 
it was called during the spring break became a

05:51.568 --> 06:11.813
major issue in the campaign. I do not know whether 
the governor had any knowledge of when spring

06:17.305 --> 06:24.515
break was and the fact that the students would be 
out of town. But it certainly made for an issue that

06:24.656 --> 06:35.431
fired up the student body in the general election 
in November later that year. And as a result, it

06:36.352 --> 06:46.587
reversed the election results in November when 
the two candidates squared off for the second

06:36.352 --> 06:46.587
time. 1984 is remembered for some other reasons in 
addition to those already mentioned. Earlier in

06:58.241 --> 07:08.856
1984, there was to be a constitutional election on 
a proposition referred to as Proposition No. 2.

07:10.867 --> 07:23.078
This proposition would restructure the 
permanent university fund and would dedicate

07:10.867 --> 07:23.078
$200 million through the higher education 
assistance fund. The higher education

07:24.920 --> 07:38.832
assistance fund would be funded through general 
revenue appropriations that would be

07:24.920 --> 07:38.832
automatically funded from the top, so to speak, 
each time the legislature met. You will recall

07:39.740 --> 08:06.692
that the schools outside of the Permanent 
University Fund that did not share in the

07:39.740 --> 08:06.692
Permanent University Fund had previously shared 
in the 10-cent ad valorem tax that was assessed

07:39.740 --> 08:06.692
throughout

07:39.740 --> 08:06.692
the state and was about to be ruled 
unconstitutional. The pure passage of

08:08.242 --> 08:15.335
Proposition 2, the Council of Governing Boards 
became very active. The Council of Governing

08:16.337 --> 08:27.778
Boards was made up of the chairman of the governing 
boards of the institutions of higher education

08:16.337 --> 08:27.778
that were state supported. In the case of Texas 
A&M, This would have normally been H.R. Bumbright

08:34.626 --> 08:44.276
of Dallas, but he requested that Mr. Joe 
Richardson of Amarillo serve in his stead on the

08:34.626 --> 08:44.276
board. This was honored, and Mr. Richardson in 
turn asked me to attend all the meetings and become

08:45.757 --> 08:58.330
involved in advising them. with regards to how to 
get Proposition 2 passed. Proposition 2 did pass

09:04.290 --> 09:12.775
in November and become a part of our Constitution, 
thereby making some changes in the Permanent

09:13.868 --> 09:39.623
University Fund by bringing several schools 
under the fund that had not previously been

09:13.868 --> 09:39.623
there and dedicating $200 million to the Higher 
Education Assistance Fund to take care of the

09:13.868 --> 09:39.623
schools that were not covered by the Permanent 
University Fund. Generally speaking, the

09:39.923 --> 09:51.902
Permanent University Fund covered those schools 
that were in the University of Texas system and the

09:39.923 --> 09:51.902
Texas A&M University system. However, we have to 
be very careful to point out that this did not cover

09:52.603 --> 10:06.184
future schools that might come into the system, 
something that we'll talk about later when the

09:52.603 --> 10:06.184
South Texas schools became desires to enter 
either the A&M system or the University of Texas

10:07.143 --> 10:13.051
system. 1984, the state of Texas experienced a 
downturn in its economic situation. This had a

10:23.365 --> 10:32.458
direct impact on the revenues that were to come to 
the state to fund state government. On making

10:34.514 --> 10:48.071
certain projections, Governor Mark White came to 
the conclusion that state agencies would have to

10:34.514 --> 10:48.071
reduce their budgets by some 13% in general 
revenue. Otherwise, the state would be floating

10:48.131 --> 10:55.881
in red ink somewhere in the future, sometime in the 
future. The governor did not have the authority to

10:57.464 --> 11:05.456
force a 13% reduction or any reduction for that 
matter. All he could do was simply ask that it be

11:06.557 --> 11:09.322
done. Only the legislature could have enforced a 
reduction in the budgets of state government. The

11:19.773 --> 11:32.773
records will probably show that most agencies and 
institutions gave up very little and did not reach

11:19.773 --> 11:32.773
the 13% goal that the governor had in mind. For 
example, Texas A&M did better than average by

11:34.195 --> 11:49.037
giving up some 9%, all of this being in reduced 
utility costs, which could not be spent for

11:34.195 --> 11:49.037
anything else the way the appropriations bill is 
written anyway. The elections were adequate

11:52.782 --> 12:10.468
enough, though, to forestall a crisis between the 
time that the governor issued the executive order

11:52.782 --> 12:10.468
and the legislature was back in session in 1985.

12:13.064 --> 12:26.046
Although a crisis was forestalled, another 
crisis was looming for higher education with

12:13.064 --> 12:26.046
regards to state appropriations. Legislative 
Budget Board meets in the fall prior to the session

12:26.066 --> 12:38.987
of the legislature convening and writes a 
proposed budget. And these budget numbers

12:39.727 --> 12:52.344
usually reflect an expenditure of funds that are 
available and allows little room for changes

12:39.727 --> 12:52.344
during the legislative session. In the year of the 
fiscal crisis, it was anticipated that most of the

12:54.287 --> 13:07.185
funds would be spent

12:54.287 --> 13:07.185
prior to the at least in the recommendations of the 
budget board prior to the session beginning.

13:15.557 --> 13:27.557
State agencies generally fared pretty well in the 
recommendations of the budget board until it came

13:15.557 --> 13:27.557
down to making appropriations for higher 
education. When those appropriations were made,

13:28.438 --> 13:30.962
it was required that a 27% reduction be made in 
general revenue for institutions of higher

13:32.782 --> 13:41.996
education. This was a much greater cut than state 
agencies had experienced and was a far greater cut

13:42.496 --> 13:57.118
than reduction in appropriations than any state 
agency or university had ever experienced in

13:57.588 --> 14:02.980
modern times. This sent shockwaves across the 
nation with regards to the terrible plight of

14:04.763 --> 14:17.571
Texas and Texas higher education.

14:21.280 --> 14:32.054
caused me to start reflecting on what might occur 
during the session once the legislature convened

14:21.280 --> 14:32.054
in January of 1985. There were two reasons for the 
27% reduction for higher education on that

14:32.254 --> 14:47.153
fateful day in December 1984 by the Legislative 
Budget Board. First is that it's the last major

14:48.685 --> 14:56.904
article in the appropriations bill to be 
considered. Therefore, it is. necessary that the

15:02.557 --> 15:22.963
recommendations by the staff be a balanced budget 
and any balancing that has to be done has to be done

15:02.557 --> 15:22.963
at the end of the appropriations process by the 
legislative budget board and its staff. Second

15:24.725 --> 15:26.387
and more important Concern and reason is that 84% 
of the budget is mandated either by statute,

15:27.498 --> 15:46.034
federal mandate, or by court order, leaving only 
16% of the budget that is not mandated. 16% is

15:46.054 --> 15:56.863
significant until you consider the fact that 
virtually all of the non-mandated

15:46.054 --> 15:56.863
appropriations is in higher education. To 
compound the of

15:59.752 --> 16:21.999
major concern was the fact that most legislators 
were not aware that such recommendations would be

15:59.752 --> 16:21.999
forthcoming once they convened in Austin and the 
appropriations recommendations were laid out.

16:24.422 --> 16:26.665
This lack of awareness concern to me about as much 
as anything else. When I considered the people

16:31.905 --> 16:46.729
that would be the key players in the 
appropriations process, I could predict as

16:31.905 --> 16:46.729
anyone could who the major players would be in the 
Senate and in the House with the exception of the

16:46.895 --> 17:15.720
person that served as Chairman of Budget and 
Oversight in the House Higher Education

16:46.895 --> 17:15.720
Committee and would serve on the Appropriations 
Committee as a member of the Budget, Chairman of

16:46.895 --> 17:15.720
the Budget and Oversight from Higher Education.

17:18.265 --> 17:26.198
This is the person that you look to to be the one to 
champion higher education.

17:28.562 --> 17:38.278
This became critically important when you 
consider the budget reductions that were going to

17:28.562 --> 17:38.278
be in the recommendations of the budget board. 
When I considered the possibilities whom I could

17:42.413 --> 17:50.802
fill that role since the position would be someone 
new. I

17:50.822 --> 18:11.543
could only come up with one person that had the 
knowledge and the savvy of the legislative

17:50.822 --> 18:11.543
operations and the courage to sit

17:50.822 --> 18:11.543
with the chairman of the Appropriations 
Committee and to stand up to the Speaker and say

18:12.907 --> 18:26.166
that higher education should not be mistreated. 
The next question, and more importantly, was how

18:27.428 --> 18:36.180
we could get the Speaker of the House to make such an 
appointment. It occurred to me that there was one

18:37.578 --> 18:45.109
person that could influence the speaker more than 
anyone else in the whole state of Texas. He

18:46.472 --> 18:56.988
happened to be a graduate of Texas A&M and was a 
close friend of the chancellor of Texas A&M

18:46.472 --> 18:56.988
University's system. So I asked the chancellor if 
he would call this individual. and urge him to

19:04.173 --> 19:18.394
contact the Speaker and urge the Speaker to make 
the appointment of this individual to the

19:04.173 --> 19:18.394
Chairman of Budget and Oversight for Higher 
Education.

19:22.560 --> 19:33.336
The appointment was made by the Speaker, much to 
our delight, and it wasn't until months later that

19:33.940 --> 19:41.587
it was confirmed that the appointment was made 
because of the phone calls that were made.

19:42.929 --> 19:56.702
Confirmed one day about midway in the session when 
the Speaker of the House stopped me in the hallway

19:42.929 --> 19:56.702
and said, you Aggies really play tough. And I knew 
exactly what he had reference to when he made that

19:58.364 --> 20:02.648
statement. He said, I know what happened. And he 
said, I just want you to know you Aggies sure do play

20:05.039 --> 20:08.443
tough. With a champion of higher education in a key 
slot, we were able to restore all but about 9% or 10%

20:10.346 --> 20:31.352
of the budget reductions that had been made by the 
recommended, at least by the Legislative Budget

20:10.346 --> 20:31.352
Board. The restoration of these funds to the 
extent that they were made was

20:33.610 --> 21:03.094
due to the effort of many, but it was very critical 
to have someone sitting on the committee that

20:33.610 --> 21:03.094
could not only relate

20:33.610 --> 21:03.094
to the chairman of the Appropriations Committee 
and the speaker, but was willing to stand up to them

21:04.475 --> 21:08.781
when the time came. Efforts were monumental on the 
part of the chairman of the Board of Regents of the

21:10.503 --> 21:28.689
University of Texas System who held a series of 
meetings in the evenings to rally support and to

21:10.503 --> 21:28.689
tell our story to the members of the legislature. I 
was invited to attend each and every one of those

21:29.750 --> 21:33.115
meetings and They were extremely effective and 
could not have been handled better than the

21:34.867 --> 21:48.163
chairman of the UT Board of Regents was able to 
handle them.

21:52.328 --> 22:00.098
To address the fiscal crisis, one of the 
approaches that was used to try to restore some

22:01.327 --> 22:14.442
physical integrity to higher education was to 
prepare alternative proposals for higher

22:01.327 --> 22:14.442
education.

22:16.902 --> 22:35.168
It became the University of Texas system's role to 
prepare these alternative proposals and take

22:16.902 --> 22:35.168
them to the key people in the legislature that were 
writing the higher education budget and tried to

22:16.902 --> 22:35.168
sell them on the IIDF. This set a pattern for years 
to come of the University of Texas preparing

22:36.690 --> 22:45.863
alternative proposals that would be to deal with 
all of higher education as a package as opposed to

22:46.028 --> 23:02.014
each institution going in and making a plea 
individually with regards to its

22:46.028 --> 23:02.014
appropriations. One of the problems and 
challenges that I always had to deal with when

23:02.935 --> 23:11.108
these proposals came forward before they were 
taken to members of the legislature, was trying to

23:11.645 --> 23:23.779
reconcile the appropriations for our A&M 
services, our agencies. The University of Texas

23:25.301 --> 23:41.280
system did not understand our agencies and were 
not that concerned and had difficulty in

23:25.301 --> 23:41.280
proposing

23:25.301 --> 23:41.280
what I considered a

23:43.268 --> 23:48.655
bare budget for these agencies. Each time we were 
successful in getting the University of Texas

23:48.676 --> 24:06.340
system to reconsider their proposal and add funds 
to the agencies' budgets prior to submitting them

23:48.676 --> 24:06.340
to members of the legislature. There were other 
distractions that we had to deal with in early 1985

24:07.670 --> 24:22.177
when the session of the legislature was well 
underway. It caused great concern. was the

24:28.038 --> 24:48.095
Comptroller of Public Accounts pronouncing that 
higher education had a $2 billion gravy bowl of

24:28.038 --> 24:48.095
funds that it could spend to make up the deficit 
that we contended that would exist if we did not get

24:28.038 --> 24:48.095
more general revenue appropriations. It took 
some time and effort to convince members of the

24:49.476 --> 24:57.943
legislature that the Comptroller was not on 
target in suggesting these funds could be spent in

24:58.430 --> 25:04.239
such a manner. These funds were out of special 
funds, special appropriations, or special

25:05.080 --> 25:24.150
grants that had been made to universities for 
scholarships and for various and other sundry

25:05.080 --> 25:24.150
purposes. programs and could not be diverted to 
general revenue appropriations to take care of

25:24.434 --> 25:32.965
operating budgets of universities. Another 
funding issue was to get implemented the changes

25:35.188 --> 25:49.125
brought about by Proposition 2 that had been made a 
part of the Texas Constitution. There were

25:49.628 --> 25:56.998
several issues that called for additional 
expenditure of general revenue funds in

25:49.628 --> 25:56.998
Proposition 2. First and foremost was a $200 
million appropriation that would go to the

25:58.560 --> 26:13.439
schools outside of the permanent university 
fund, and this was called the Higher Education

25:58.560 --> 26:13.439
Assistance Fund. These funds had to be set aside 
out of the general revenue appropriation's prior

26:19.919 --> 26:25.390
to any operating budgets being allocated funds.

26:28.176 --> 26:38.316
In addition, some other changes that were made in 
Proposition 2 dealt with the allocation of

26:28.176 --> 26:38.316
additional funds to Prairie View. $6 million each 
year for the next 10 years to come from the

26:39.258 --> 26:53.959
University of Texas System's portion of the 
Permanent University Fund, and with A&M

26:39.258 --> 26:53.959
providing an equitable portion. That was in 1985

26:55.522 --> 27:02.532
when it became... first became law as a part of the 
Constitution. And since then, University of

27:07.762 --> 27:15.879
Texas has completed its obligation of providing 
$6 million for 10 years. But to my knowledge, we

27:16.540 --> 27:23.575
still have not clearly defined what is an 
equitable portion for Prairie View. The other

27:25.343 --> 27:30.510
changes that were made was the addition of other 
schools under the permanent university fund. In

27:31.311 --> 27:37.779
the case of the Texas A&M University system, we 
were adding the Texas A&M University at

27:31.311 --> 27:37.779
Galveston. It also made a change with regards to 
allocation of funds to our agencies in the Texas

27:39.602 --> 27:52.178
A&M University system. In the past, the A&M 
agencies had to get legislative approval to sell

27:53.238 --> 28:14.554
bonds and use bond proceeds for construction at 
facilities other than on the A&M campus at College

27:53.238 --> 28:14.554
Station. This proposition changed that where the 
allocation and approval could be made by the A&M

28:16.222 --> 28:26.735
System Board of Regents.

28:32.302 --> 28:40.812
A final change brought about by Proposition 2 in 
1984 was providing access of the system offices of

28:40.977 --> 28:57.577
the Texas A&M University System and the 
University of Texas System to the available

28:40.977 --> 28:57.577
university fund

28:40.977 --> 28:57.577
for their operational expenses. This provision 
in the proposition has obviously led to a decline

29:00.000 --> 29:07.930
in the availability of general revenue 
appropriations by the legislature to the system

29:08.804 --> 29:15.213
offices. Since proposition to system offices of 
A&M and the University of Texas system have

29:16.855 --> 29:28.150
received only a token amount of general revenue 
appropriations from the legislature. Mentioned

29:29.252 --> 29:34.018
before 1985, the legislative session presented 
some very difficult times for higher education

29:35.213 --> 29:53.922
because of the budgetary cuts going into the 
session and coming out of the session with still

29:35.213 --> 29:53.922
about a nine percent reduction in general revenue 
appropriations for higher education. The

29:54.863 --> 30:02.976
actions that was taken by the Texas A&M University 
System Board of Regents to alleviate some of the

30:02.956 --> 30:22.602
problem, particularly on the main campus of Texas 
A&M University, was to refund

30:02.956 --> 30:22.602
most of the bonds that had been previously funded 
at higher rates.

30:25.231 --> 30:33.180
than the interest rates that were prevailing in 
1985 and 1986. Refunding these bonds, about $50

30:34.621 --> 30:47.275
million was freed up for one-time funding by the 
Texas A&M University System Board of Regents. The

